# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: julia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:julia/getting-started] Julia installation is straightforward, whether using precompiled binaries or compiling from source.
[src:julia/getting-started] Download and install Julia by following the instructions at https://julialang.org/install/.
[src:julia/getting-started] If you are coming to Julia from one of the following languages, then you should start by reading the section on noteworthy differences from MATLAB, R, Python, C/C++ or Common Lisp.
[src:julia/getting-started] This will help you avoid some common pitfalls since Julia differs from those languages in many subtle ways.
[src:julia/getting-started] To exit the interactive session, type `CTRL-D` (press the Control/`^` key together with the `d` key), or type `exit()`.
[src:julia/getting-started] When run in interactive mode, `julia` displays a banner and prompts the user for input.
[src:julia/getting-started] Once the user has entered a complete expression, such as `1 + 2`, and hits enter, the interactive session evaluates the expression and shows its value.
[src:julia/getting-started] If an expression is entered into an interactive session with a trailing semicolon, its value is not shown.
[src:julia/getting-started] The variable `ans` is bound to the value of the last evaluated expression whether it is shown or not.
[src:julia/getting-started] The `ans` variable is only bound in interactive sessions, not when Julia code is run in other ways.
[src:julia/getting-started] To evaluate expressions written in a source file `file.jl`, write `include("file.jl")`.
[src:julia/getting-started] You can pass additional arguments to Julia, and to your program `script.jl`.
[src:julia/getting-started] A detailed list of all the available options can be found under Command-line Interface.
[src:julia/getting-started] A curated list of useful learning resources to help new users get started can be found on the learning page of the main Julia website.
[src:julia/getting-started] You can use the REPL as a learning resource by switching into the help mode.
[src:julia/getting-started] Switch to help mode by pressing `?` at an empty `julia>` prompt, before typing anything else.
[src:julia/getting-started] Typing a keyword in help mode will fetch the documentation for it, along with examples.
[src:julia/getting-started] Similarly for most functions or other objects you might encounter!
[src:julia/getting-started] If you already know Julia a bit, you might want to peek ahead at Performance Tips and Workflow Tips, or check out the comprehensive ModernJuliaWorkflows blog.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Julia, like most technical computing languages, provides a first-class array implementation.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Most technical computing languages pay a lot of attention to their array implementation at the expense of other containers.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Julia does not treat arrays in any special way.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] The array library is implemented almost completely in Julia itself, and derives its performance from the compiler, just like any other code written in Julia.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] As such, it's also possible to define custom array types by inheriting from `AbstractArray`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] See the manual section on the AbstractArray interface for more details on implementing a custom array type.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] An array is a collection of objects stored in a multi-dimensional grid.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Zero-dimensional arrays are allowed, see this FAQ entry.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] In the most general case, an array may contain objects of type `Any`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] For most computational purposes, arrays should contain objects of a more specific type, such as `Float64` or `Int32`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] In general, unlike many other technical computing languages, Julia does not expect programs to be written in a vectorized style for performance.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Julia's compiler uses type inference and generates optimized code for scalar array indexing, allowing programs to be written in a style that is convenient and readable, without sacrificing performance, and using less memory at times.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] In Julia, all arguments to functions are passed by sharing (i.e. by pointers).
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Some technical computing languages pass arrays by value, and while this prevents accidental modification by callees of a value in the caller, it makes avoiding unwanted copying of arrays difficult.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] By convention, a function name ending with a `!` indicates that it will mutate or destroy the value of one or more of its arguments (compare, for example, `sort` and `sort!`).
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Callees must make explicit copies to ensure that they don't modify inputs that they don't intend to change.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Many non-mutating functions are implemented by calling a function of the same name with an added `!` at the end on an explicit copy of the input, and returning that copy.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Many functions for constructing and initializing arrays are provided.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] In the following list of such functions, calls with a `dims...` argument can either take a single tuple of dimension sizes or a series of dimension sizes passed as a variable number of arguments.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Most of these functions also accept a first input `T`, which is the element type of the array.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] If the type `T` is omitted it will default to `Float64`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Here, `(2, 3)` is a `Tuple` and the first argument — the element type — is optional, defaulting to `Float64`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Arrays can also be directly constructed with square braces; the syntax `[A, B, C, ...]` creates a one-dimensional array (i.e., a vector) containing the comma-separated arguments as its elements.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] The element type (`eltype`) of the resulting array is automatically determined by the types of the arguments inside the braces.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] If all the arguments are the same type, then that is its `eltype`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] If they all have a common promotion type then they get converted to that type using `convert` and that type is the array's `eltype`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Otherwise, a heterogeneous array that can hold anything — a `Vector{Any}` — is constructed; this includes the literal `[]` where no arguments are given.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Array literal can be typed with the syntax `T[A, B, C, ...]` where `T` is a type.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] If the arguments inside the square brackets are separated by single semicolons (`;`) or newlines instead of commas, then their contents are *vertically concatenated* together instead of the arguments being used as elements themselves.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Similarly, if the arguments are separated by tabs or spaces or double semicolons, then their contents are *horizontally concatenated* together.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Single semicolons (or newlines) and spaces (or tabs) can be combined to concatenate both horizontally and vertically at the same time.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Spaces (and tabs) have a higher precedence than semicolons, performing any horizontal concatenations first and then concatenating the result.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Using double semicolons for the horizontal concatenation, on the other hand, performs any vertical concatenations before horizontally concatenating the result.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Just as `;` and `;;` concatenate in the first and second dimension, using more semicolons extends this same general scheme.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] The number of semicolons in the separator specifies the particular dimension, so `;;;` concatenates in the third dimension, `;;;;` in the 4th, and so on.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Fewer semicolons take precedence, so the lower dimensions are generally concatenated first.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Like before, spaces (and tabs) for horizontal concatenation have a higher precedence than any number of semicolons.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Although they both mean concatenation in the second dimension, spaces (or tabs) and `;;` cannot appear in the same array expression unless the double semicolon is simply serving as a "line continuation" character.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] This allows a single horizontal concatenation to span multiple lines (without the line break being interpreted as a vertical concatenation).
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Terminating semicolons may also be used to add trailing length 1 dimensions.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] More generally, concatenation can be accomplished through the `cat` function.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] An array with a specific element type can be constructed using the syntax `T[A, B, C, ...]`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] This will construct a 1-d array with element type `T`, initialized to contain elements `A`, `B`, `C`, etc.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] For example, `Any[x, y, z]` constructs a heterogeneous array that can contain any values.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Concatenation syntax can similarly be prefixed with a type to specify the element type of the result.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Comprehensions provide a general and powerful way to construct arrays.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] The meaning of this form is that `F(x,y,...)` is evaluated with the variables `x`, `y`, etc. taking on each value in their given list of values.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Values can be specified as any iterable object, but will commonly be ranges like `1:n` or `2:(n-1)`, or explicit arrays of values like `[1.2, 3.4, 5.7]`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] The result is an N-d dense array with dimensions that are the concatenation of the dimensions of the variable ranges `rx`, `ry`, etc. and each `F(x,y,...)` evaluation returns a scalar.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] The resulting array type depends on the types of the computed elements just like array literals do.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] In order to control the type explicitly, a type can be prepended to the comprehension.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Comprehensions can also be written without the enclosing square brackets, producing an object known as a generator.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] This object can be iterated to produce values on demand, instead of allocating an array and storing them in advance (see Iteration).
[src:julia/manual-arrays] All comma-separated expressions after `for` are interpreted as ranges.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Generators are implemented via inner functions.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Just like inner functions used elsewhere in the language, variables from the enclosing scope can be "captured" in the inner function.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] For example, `sum(p[i] - q[i] for i=1:n)` captures the three variables `p`, `q` and `n` from the enclosing scope.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Captured variables can present performance challenges; see performance tips.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] In such cases, the result is always 1-d.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] where each `I_k` may be a scalar integer, an array of integers, or any other supported index.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] This includes `Colon` (`:`) to select all indices within the entire dimension, ranges of the form `a:c` or `a:b:c` to select contiguous or strided subsections, and arrays of booleans to select elements at their `true` indices.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] If all the indices are scalars, then the result `X` is a single element from the array `A`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Otherwise, `X` is an array with the same number of dimensions as the sum of the dimensionalities of all the indices.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Note how the size of the resulting array is different in the last two cases.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] If `I_1` is changed to a two-dimensional matrix, then `X` becomes an `n+1`-dimensional array of shape `(size(I_1, 1), size(I_1, 2), length(I_2), ..., length(I_n))`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] All dimensions indexed with scalars are dropped.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] For example, if `J` is an array of indices, then the result of `A[2, J, 3]` is an array with size `size(J)`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Its `j`th element is populated by `A[2, J[j], 3]`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] As a special part of this syntax, the `end` keyword may be used to represent the last index of each dimension within the indexing brackets, as determined by the size of the innermost array being indexed.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] If all indices `I_k` are integers, then the value in location `I_1, I_2, ..., I_n` of `A` is overwritten with the value of `X`, `convert`ing to the `eltype` of `A` if necessary.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] If any index `I_k` is itself an array, then the right hand side `X` must also be an array with the same shape as the result of indexing `A[I_1, I_2, ..., I_n]` or a vector with the same number of elements.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Just as in Indexing, the `end` keyword may be used to represent the last index of each dimension within the indexing brackets, as determined by the size of the array being assigned into.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] An object that represents an array of scalar indices and can be converted to such by `to_indices`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] The special `CartesianIndex{N}` object represents a scalar index that behaves like an `N`-tuple of integers spanning multiple dimensions.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Considered alone, this may seem relatively trivial; `CartesianIndex` simply gathers multiple integers together into one object that represents a single multidimensional index.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] When combined with other indexing forms and iterators that yield `CartesianIndex`es, however, this can produce very elegant and efficient code.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] See Iteration below, and for some more advanced examples, see this blog post on multidimensional algorithms and iteration.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Arrays of `CartesianIndex{N}` are also supported.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] They represent a collection of scalar indices that each span `N` dimensions, enabling a form of indexing that is sometimes referred to as pointwise indexing.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] This can be expressed much more simply with dot broadcasting and by combining it with a normal integer index (instead of extracting the first `page` from `A` as a separate step).
[src:julia/manual-arrays] `CartesianIndex` and arrays of `CartesianIndex` are not compatible with the `end` keyword to represent the last index of a dimension.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Do not use `end` in indexing expressions that may contain either `CartesianIndex` or arrays thereof.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Often referred to as logical indexing or indexing with a logical mask, indexing by a boolean array selects elements at the indices where its values are `true`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Indexing by a boolean vector `B` is effectively the same as indexing by the vector of integers that is returned by `findall(B)`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Similarly, indexing by a `N`-dimensional boolean array is effectively the same as indexing by the vector of `CartesianIndex{N}`s where its values are `true`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] A logical index must be an array of the same shape as the dimension(s) it indexes into, or it must be the only index provided and match the shape of the one-dimensional reshaped view of the array it indexes into.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] It is generally more efficient to use boolean arrays as indices directly instead of first calling `findall`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] The ordinary way to index into an `N`-dimensional array is to use exactly `N` indices; each index selects the position(s) in its particular dimension.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] For example, in the three-dimensional array `A = rand(4, 3, 2)`, `A[2, 3, 1]` will select the number in the second row of the third column in the first "page" of the array.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] This is often referred to as *cartesian indexing*.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] When exactly one index `i` is provided, that index no longer represents a location in a particular dimension of the array.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Instead, it selects the `i`th element using the column-major iteration order that linearly spans the entire array.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] It essentially treats the array as though it had been reshaped into a one-dimensional vector with `vec`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] A linear index into the array `A` can be converted to a `CartesianIndex` for cartesian indexing with `CartesianIndices(A)[i]` (see `CartesianIndices`), and a set of `N` cartesian indices can be converted to a linear index with `LinearIndices(A)[i_1, i_2, ..., i_N]` (see `LinearIndices`).
[src:julia/manual-arrays] It's important to note that there's a very large asymmetry in the performance of these conversions.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Converting a linear index to a set of cartesian indices requires dividing and taking the remainder, whereas going the other way is just multiplies and adds.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] In modern processors, integer division can be 10-50 times slower than multiplication.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] While some arrays — like `Array` itself — are implemented using a linear chunk of memory and directly use a linear index in their implementations, other arrays — like `Diagonal` — need the full set of cartesian indices to do their lookup (see `IndexStyle` to introspect which is which).
[src:julia/manual-arrays] When iterating over all the indices for an array, it is better to iterate over `eachindex(A)` instead of `1:length(A)`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Not only will this be faster in cases where `A` is `IndexCartesian`, but it will also support arrays with custom indexing, such as OffsetArrays.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] If only the values are needed, then is better to just iterate the array directly, i.e.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] In addition to linear indexing, an `N`-dimensional array may be indexed with fewer or more than `N` indices in certain situations.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Indices may be omitted if the trailing dimensions that are not indexed into are all length one.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] In other words, trailing indices can be omitted only if there is only one possible value that those omitted indices could be for an in-bounds indexing expression.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] For example, a four-dimensional array with size `(3, 4, 2, 1)` may be indexed with only three indices as the dimension that gets skipped (the fourth dimension) has length one.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Note that linear indexing takes precedence over this rule.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] When omitting *all* indices with `A[]`, this semantic provides a simple idiom to retrieve the only element in an array and simultaneously ensure that there was only one element.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Similarly, more than `N` indices may be provided if all the indices beyond the dimensionality of the array are `1` (or more generally are the first and only element of `axes(A, d)` where `d` is that particular dimension number).
[src:julia/manual-arrays] The first construct is used when you need the value, but not index, of each element.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] In contrast with `for i = 1:length(A)`, iterating with `eachindex` provides an efficient way to iterate over any array type.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Besides, this also supports generic arrays with custom indexing such as OffsetArrays.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] This setting will cause `eachindex` iteration over a `MyArray` to use integers.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] If you don't specify this trait, the default value `IndexCartesian()` is used.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] To enable convenient vectorization of mathematical and other operations, Julia provides the dot syntax `f.(args...)`, e.g.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] `sin.(x)` or `min.(x, y)`, for elementwise operations over arrays or mixtures of arrays and scalars (a Broadcasting operation); these have the additional advantage of "fusing" into a single loop when combined with other dot calls, e.g.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Also, *every* binary operator supports a dot version that can be applied to arrays (and combinations of arrays and scalars) in such fused broadcasting operations, e.g.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Note that comparisons such as `==` operate on whole arrays, giving a single boolean answer.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Use dot operators like `.==` for elementwise comparisons.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Also notice the difference between `max.(a,b)`, which `broadcast`s `max` elementwise over `a` and `b`, and `maximum(a)`, which finds the largest value within `a`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] The same relationship holds for `min.(a, b)` and `minimum(a)`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] It is sometimes useful to perform element-by-element binary operations on arrays of different sizes, such as adding a vector to each column of a matrix.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Dotted operators such as `.+` and `.*` are equivalent to `broadcast` calls (except that they fuse, as described above).
[src:julia/manual-arrays] There is also a `broadcast!` function to specify an explicit destination (which can also be accessed in a fusing fashion by `.=` assignment).
[src:julia/manual-arrays] In fact, `f.(args...)` is equivalent to `broadcast(f, args...)`, providing a convenient syntax to broadcast any function (dot syntax).
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Nested "dot calls" `f.(...)` (including calls to `.+` etcetera) automatically fuse into a single `broadcast` call.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Additionally, `broadcast` is not limited to arrays (see the function documentation); it also handles scalars, tuples and other collections.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] By default, only some argument types are considered scalars, including (but not limited to) `Number`s, `String`s, `Symbol`s, `Type`s, `Function`s and some common singletons like `missing` and `nothing`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] All other arguments are iterated over or indexed into elementwise.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Sometimes, you want a container (like an array) that would normally participate in broadcast to be "protected" from broadcast's behavior of iterating over all of its elements.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] By placing it inside another container (like a single element `Tuple`) broadcast will treat it as a single value.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] The base array type in Julia is the abstract type `AbstractArray{T,N}`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] It is parameterized by the number of dimensions `N` and the element type `T`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] `AbstractVector` and `AbstractMatrix` are aliases for the 1-d and 2-d cases.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Operations on `AbstractArray` objects are defined using higher level operators and functions, in a way that is independent of the underlying storage.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] These operations generally work correctly as a fallback for any specific array implementation.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] The `AbstractArray` type includes anything vaguely array-like, and implementations of it might be quite different from conventional arrays.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] For example, elements might be computed on request rather than stored.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] However, any concrete `AbstractArray{T,N}` type should generally implement at least `size(A)` (returning an `Int` tuple), `getindex(A, i)` and `getindex(A, i1, ..., iN)`; mutable arrays should also implement `setindex!`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] It is recommended that these operations have nearly constant time complexity, as otherwise some array functions may be unexpectedly slow.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Concrete types should also typically provide a `similar(A, T=eltype(A), dims=size(A))` method, which is used to allocate a similar array for `copy` and other out-of-place operations.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] No matter how an `AbstractArray{T,N}` is represented internally, `T` is the type of object returned by *integer* indexing (`A[1, ..., 1]`, when `A` is not empty) and `N` should be the length of the tuple returned by `size`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] For more details on defining custom `AbstractArray` implementations, see the array interface guide in the interfaces chapter.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] `DenseArray` is an abstract subtype of `AbstractArray` intended to include all arrays where elements are stored contiguously in column-major order (see additional notes in Performance Tips).
[src:julia/manual-arrays] The `Array` type is a specific instance of `DenseArray`; `Vector` and `Matrix` are aliases for the 1-d and 2-d cases.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Very few operations are implemented specifically for `Array` beyond those that are required for all `AbstractArray`s; much of the array library is implemented in a generic manner that allows all custom arrays to behave similarly.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] `SubArray` is a specialization of `AbstractArray` that performs indexing by sharing memory with the original array rather than by copying it.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] A `SubArray` is created with the `view` function, which is called the same way as `getindex` (with an array and a series of index arguments).
[src:julia/manual-arrays] The result of `view` looks the same as the result of `getindex`, except the data is left in place.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] `view` stores the input index vectors in a `SubArray` object, which can later be used to index the original array indirectly.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] By putting the `@views` macro in front of an expression or block of code, any `array[...]` slice in that expression will be converted to create a `SubArray` view instead.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] `BitArray`s are space-efficient "packed" boolean arrays, which store one bit per boolean value.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] They can be used similarly to `Array{Bool}` arrays (which store one byte per boolean value), and can be converted to/from the latter via `Array(bitarray)` and `BitArray(array)`, respectively.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] An array is "strided" if it is stored in memory with well-defined spacings (strides) between its elements.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] A strided array with a supported element type may be passed to an external (non-Julia) library like BLAS or LAPACK by simply passing its `pointer` and the stride for each dimension.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] The `stride(A, d)` is the distance between elements along dimension `d`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] For example, the builtin `Array` returned by `rand(5,7,2)` has its elements arranged contiguously in column major order.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] The stride of the second dimension is the spacing between elements in the same row, skipping as many elements as there are in a single column (`5`).
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Similarly, jumping between the two "pages" (in the third dimension) requires skipping `5*7 == 35` elements.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] In this particular case, the number of elements skipped *in memory* matches the number of *linear indices* skipped.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] This is only the case for contiguous arrays like `Array` (and other `DenseArray` subtypes) and is not true in general.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Views with range indices are a good example of *non-contiguous* strided arrays; consider `V = @view A[1:3:4, 2:2:6, 2:-1:1]`.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] This view `V` refers to the same memory as `A` but is skipping and re-arranging some of its elements.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] The third dimension is interesting because its order is reversed!
[src:julia/manual-arrays] Thus to get from the first "page" to the second one it must go *backwards* in memory, and so its stride in this dimension is negative!
[src:julia/manual-arrays] This means that the `pointer` for `V` is actually pointing into the middle of `A`'s memory block, and it refers to elements both backwards and forwards in memory.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] See the interface guide for strided arrays for more details on defining your own strided arrays.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] `StridedVector` and `StridedMatrix` are convenient aliases for many of the builtin array types that are considered strided arrays, allowing them to dispatch to select specialized implementations that call highly tuned and optimized BLAS and LAPACK functions using just the pointer and strides.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] It is worth emphasizing that strides are about offsets in memory rather than indexing.
[src:julia/manual-arrays] If you are looking to convert between linear (single-index) indexing and cartesian (multi-index) indexing, see `LinearIndices` and `CartesianIndices`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] In Julia, a function is an object that maps a tuple of argument values to a return value.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Julia functions are not pure mathematical functions, because they can alter and be affected by the global state of the program.
[src:julia/manual-functions] This function accepts two arguments `x` and `y` and returns the value of the last expression evaluated, which is `x + y`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] There is a second, more terse syntax for defining a function in Julia.
[src:julia/manual-functions] In the assignment form, the body of the function must be a single expression, although it can be a compound expression (see Compound Expressions).
[src:julia/manual-functions] Short, simple function definitions are common in Julia.
[src:julia/manual-functions] The short function syntax is accordingly quite idiomatic, considerably reducing both typing and visual noise.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Julia function arguments follow a convention sometimes called "pass-by-sharing", which means that values are not copied when they are passed to functions.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Function arguments themselves act as new variable *bindings* (new "names" that can refer to values), much like assignments `argument_name = argument_value`, so that the objects they refer to are identical to the passed values.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Modifications to mutable values (such as `Array`s) made within a function will be visible to the caller.
[src:julia/manual-functions] The statement `x[1] = 42` *mutates* the object `x`, and hence this change *will* be visible in the array passed by the caller for this argument.
[src:julia/manual-functions] On the other hand, the assignment `y = 7 + y` changes the *binding* ("name") `y` to refer to a new value `7 + y`, rather than mutating the *original* object referred to by `y`, and hence does *not* change the corresponding argument passed by the caller.
[src:julia/manual-functions] As a common convention in Julia (not a syntactic requirement), such a function would typically be named `f!(x, y)` rather than `f(x, y)`, as a visual reminder at the call site that at least one of the arguments (often the first one) is being mutated.
[src:julia/manual-functions] The behavior of a mutating function can be unexpected when a mutated argument shares memory with another argument, a situation known as aliasing (e.g. when one is a view of the other).
[src:julia/manual-functions] Unless the function docstring explicitly indicates that aliasing produces the expected result, it is the responsibility of the caller to ensure proper behavior on such inputs.
[src:julia/manual-functions] You can declare the types of function arguments by appending `::TypeName` to the argument name, as usual for Type Declarations in Julia.
[src:julia/manual-functions] and the `::Integer` specification means that it will only be callable when `n` is a subtype of the abstract `Integer` type.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Argument-type declarations **normally have no impact on performance**: regardless of what argument types (if any) are declared, Julia compiles a specialized version of the function for the actual argument types passed by the caller.
[src:julia/manual-functions] For example, calling `fib(1)` will trigger the compilation of specialized version of `fib` optimized specifically for `Int` arguments, which is then re-used if `fib(7)` or `fib(15)` are called.
[src:julia/manual-functions] However, it is a **common mistake to overly restrict the argument types**, which can unnecessarily limit the applicability of the function and prevent it from being re-used in circumstances you did not anticipate.
[src:julia/manual-functions] If we had declared our function as `fib(n::Int)`, however, the application to `BigInt` would have been prevented for no reason.
[src:julia/manual-functions] In general, you should use the most general applicable abstract types for arguments, and **when in doubt, omit the argument types**.
[src:julia/manual-functions] You can always add argument-type specifications later if they become necessary, and you don't sacrifice performance or functionality by omitting them.
[src:julia/manual-functions] The value returned by a function is the value of the last expression evaluated, which, by default, is the last expression in the body of the function definition.
[src:julia/manual-functions] In the example function, `f`, from the previous section this is the value of the expression `x + y`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Of course, in a purely linear function body like `g`, the usage of `return` is pointless since the expression `x + y` is never evaluated and we could simply make `x * y` the last expression in the function and omit the `return`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] In conjunction with other control flow, however, `return` is of real use.
[src:julia/manual-functions] There are three possible points of return from this function, returning the values of three different expressions, depending on the values of `x` and `y`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] The `return` on the last line could be omitted since it is the last expression.
[src:julia/manual-functions] A return type can be specified in the function declaration using the `::` operator.
[src:julia/manual-functions] This converts the return value to the specified type.
[src:julia/manual-functions] This function will always return an `Int8` regardless of the types of `x` and `y`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] See Type Declarations for more on return types.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Return type declarations are **rarely used** in Julia: in general, you should instead write "type-stable" functions in which Julia's compiler can automatically infer the return type.
[src:julia/manual-functions] For more information, see the Performance Tips chapter.
[src:julia/manual-functions] This is a *convention* in the sense that `nothing` is not a Julia keyword but only a singleton object of type `Nothing`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Also, you may notice that the `printx` function example above is contrived, because `println` already returns `nothing`, so that the `return` line is redundant.
[src:julia/manual-functions] There are two possible shortened forms for the `return nothing` expression.
[src:julia/manual-functions] On the one hand, the `return` keyword implicitly returns `nothing`, so it can be used alone.
[src:julia/manual-functions] On the other hand, since functions implicitly return their last expression evaluated, `nothing` can be used alone when it's the last expression.
[src:julia/manual-functions] The preference for the expression `return nothing` as opposed to `return` or `nothing` alone is a matter of coding style.
[src:julia/manual-functions] In Julia, most operators are just functions with support for special syntax.
[src:julia/manual-functions] (The exceptions are operators with special evaluation semantics like `&&` and `||`.
