[src:julia/manual-functions] The primary use for anonymous functions is passing them to functions which take other functions as arguments.
[src:julia/manual-functions] This is fine if a named function effecting the transform already exists to pass as the first argument to `map`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Often, however, a ready-to-use, named function does not exist.
[src:julia/manual-functions] An anonymous function accepting multiple arguments can be written using the syntax `(x,y,z)->2x+y-z`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Argument-type declarations for anonymous functions work as for named functions, for example `x::Integer->2x`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] The return type of an anonymous function cannot be specified.
[src:julia/manual-functions] A zero-argument anonymous function can be written as `()->2+2`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] The idea of a function with no arguments may seem strange, but is useful in cases where a result cannot (or should not) be precomputed.
[src:julia/manual-functions] For example, Julia has a zero-argument `time` function that returns the current time in seconds, and thus `seconds = ()->round(Int, time())` is an anonymous function that returns this time rounded to the nearest integer assigned to the variable `seconds`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Each time this anonymous function is called as `seconds()` the current time will be calculated and returned.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Julia has a built-in data structure called a *tuple* that is closely related to function arguments and return values.
[src:julia/manual-functions] A tuple is a fixed-length container that can hold any values, but cannot be modified (it is *immutable*).
[src:julia/manual-functions] Notice that a length-1 tuple must be written with a comma, `(1,)`, since `(1)` would just be a parenthesized value.
[src:julia/manual-functions] `()` represents the empty (length-0) tuple.
[src:julia/manual-functions] The fields of named tuples can be accessed by name using dot syntax (`x.a`) in addition to the regular indexing syntax (`x[1]` or `x[:a]`).
[src:julia/manual-functions] The value on the right should be an iterator (see Iteration interface) at least as long as the number of variables on the left (any excess elements of the iterator are ignored).
[src:julia/manual-functions] This can be used to return multiple values from functions by returning a tuple or other iterable value.
[src:julia/manual-functions] See `Base.rest` for details on the precise handling and customization for specific iterators.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Slurping in assignments can also occur in any other position.
[src:julia/manual-functions] As opposed to slurping the end of a collection however, this will always be eager.
[src:julia/manual-functions] This is implemented in terms of the function `Base.split_rest`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Note that for variadic function definitions, slurping is still only allowed in final position.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Instead of destructuring based on iteration, the right side of assignments can also be destructured using property names.
[src:julia/manual-functions] The destructuring feature can also be used within a function argument.
