[src:julia/manual-functions] It is often convenient to be able to write functions taking an arbitrary number of arguments.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Such functions are traditionally known as "varargs" functions, which is short for "variable number of arguments".
[src:julia/manual-functions] In all these cases, `x` is bound to a tuple of the trailing values passed to `bar`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] It is possible to constrain the number of values passed as a variable argument; this will be discussed later in Parametrically-constrained Varargs methods.
[src:julia/manual-functions] On the flip side, it is often handy to "splat" the values contained in an iterable collection into a function call as individual arguments.
[src:julia/manual-functions] In this case a tuple of values is spliced into a varargs call precisely where the variable number of arguments go.
[src:julia/manual-functions] As you can see, if the wrong number of elements are in the splatted container, then the function call will fail, just as it would if too many arguments were given explicitly.
[src:julia/manual-functions] It is often possible to provide sensible default values for function arguments.
[src:julia/manual-functions] This can save users from having to pass every argument on every call.
[src:julia/manual-functions] For example, the function `Date(y, [m, d])` from `Dates` module constructs a `Date` type for a given year `y`, month `m` and day `d`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] However, `m` and `d` arguments are optional and their default value is `1`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Observe, that this definition calls another method of the `Date` function that takes one argument of type `UTInstant{Day}`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Optional arguments are actually just a convenient syntax for writing multiple method definitions with different numbers of arguments (see Note on Optional and keyword Arguments).
[src:julia/manual-functions] Some functions need a large number of arguments, or have a large number of behaviors.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Remembering how to call such functions can be difficult.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Keyword arguments can make these complex interfaces easier to use and extend by allowing arguments to be identified by name instead of only by position.
[src:julia/manual-functions] For example, consider a function `plot` that plots a line.
[src:julia/manual-functions] This function might have many options, for controlling line style, width, color, and so on.
[src:julia/manual-functions] If it accepts keyword arguments, a possible call might look like `plot(x, y, width=2)`, where we have chosen to specify only line width.
[src:julia/manual-functions] The call is easier to read, since we can label an argument with its meaning.
[src:julia/manual-functions] It also becomes possible to pass any subset of a large number of arguments, in any order.
[src:julia/manual-functions] When the function is called, the semicolon is optional: one can either call `plot(x, y, width=2)` or `plot(x, y; width=2)`, but the former style is more common.
[src:julia/manual-functions] An explicit semicolon is required only for passing varargs or computed keywords as described below.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Keyword argument default values are evaluated only when necessary (when a corresponding keyword argument is not passed), and in left-to-right order.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Therefore default expressions may refer to prior keyword arguments.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Inside `f`, `kwargs` will be an immutable key-value iterator over a named tuple.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Named tuples (as well as dictionaries with keys of `Symbol`, and other iterators yielding two-value collections with symbol as first values) can be passed as keyword arguments using a semicolon in a call, e.g.
[src:julia/manual-functions] One can also pass `key => value` expressions after a semicolon.
[src:julia/manual-functions] For example, `plot(x, y; :width => 2)` is equivalent to `plot(x, y, width=2)`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] This is useful in situations where the keyword name is computed at runtime.
[src:julia/manual-functions] When a bare identifier or dot expression occurs after a semicolon, the keyword argument name is implied by the identifier or field name.
[src:julia/manual-functions] For example `plot(x, y; width)` is equivalent to `plot(x, y; width=width)` and `plot(x, y; options.width)` is equivalent to `plot(x, y; width=options.width)`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] The nature of keyword arguments makes it possible to specify the same argument more than once.
[src:julia/manual-functions] For example, in the call `plot(x, y; options..., width=2)` it is possible that the `options` structure also contains a value for `width`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] In such a case the rightmost occurrence takes precedence; in this example, `width` is certain to have the value `2`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] However, explicitly specifying the same keyword argument multiple times, for example `plot(x, y, width=2, width=3)`, is not allowed and results in a syntax error.
[src:julia/manual-functions] When optional and keyword argument default expressions are evaluated, only *previous* arguments are in scope.
[src:julia/manual-functions] the `b` in `a=b` refers to a `b` in an outer scope, not the subsequent argument `b`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Passing functions as arguments to other functions is a powerful technique, but the syntax for it is not always convenient.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Such calls are especially awkward to write when the function argument requires multiple lines.
[src:julia/manual-functions] The `do x` syntax creates an anonymous function with argument `x` and passes the anonymous function as the first argument to the "outer" function - `map` in this example.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Similarly, `do a,b` would create a two-argument anonymous function.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Note that `do (a,b)` would create a one-argument anonymous function, whose argument is a tuple to be deconstructed.
[src:julia/manual-functions] A plain `do` would declare that what follows is an anonymous function of the form `() -> ...`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] How these arguments are initialized depends on the "outer" function; here, `map` will sequentially set `x` to `A`, `B`, `C`, calling the anonymous function on each, just as would happen in the syntax `map(func, [A, B, C])`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] This syntax makes it easier to use functions to effectively extend the language, since calls look like normal code blocks.
[src:julia/manual-functions] There are many possible uses quite different from `map`, such as managing system state.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Here, `open` first opens the file for writing and then passes the resulting output stream to the anonymous function you defined in the `do ... end` block.
[src:julia/manual-functions] After your function exits, `open` will make sure that the stream is properly closed, regardless of whether your function exited normally or threw an exception.
[src:julia/manual-functions] With the `do` block syntax, it helps to check the documentation or implementation to know how the arguments of the user function are initialized.
[src:julia/manual-functions] A `do` block, like any other inner function, can "capture" variables from its enclosing scope.
[src:julia/manual-functions] For example, the variable `data` in the above example of `open...do` is captured from the outer scope.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Captured variables can create performance challenges as discussed in performance tips.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Functions in Julia can be combined by composing or piping (chaining) them together.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Function composition is when you combine functions together and apply the resulting composition to arguments.
[src:julia/manual-functions] You use the function composition operator (`∘`) to compose the functions, so `(f ∘ g)(args...; kw...)` is the same as `f(g(args...; kw...))`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] You can type the composition operator at the REPL and suitably-configured editors using `\circ<tab>`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] This adds the numbers first, then finds the square root of the result.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Here, the total produced by `sum` is passed to the `sqrt` function.
[src:julia/manual-functions] The pipe operator can also be used with broadcasting, as `.|>`, to provide a useful combination of the chaining/piping and dot vectorization syntax (described below).
[src:julia/manual-functions] When combining pipes with anonymous functions, parentheses must be used if subsequent pipes are not to be parsed as part of the anonymous function's body.
[src:julia/manual-functions] In technical-computing languages, it is common to have "vectorized" versions of functions, which simply apply a given function `f(x)` to each element of an array `A` to yield a new array via `f(A)`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] This kind of syntax is convenient for data processing, but in other languages vectorization is also often required for performance: if loops are slow, the "vectorized" version of a function can call fast library code written in a low-level language.
[src:julia/manual-functions] In Julia, vectorized functions are *not* required for performance, and indeed it is often beneficial to write your own loops (see Performance Tips), but they can still be convenient.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Therefore, *any* Julia function `f` can be applied elementwise to any array (or other collection) with the syntax `f.(A)`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Of course, you can omit the dot if you write a specialized "vector" method of `f`, e.g. via `f(A::AbstractArray) = map(f, A)`, and this is just as efficient as `f.(A)`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] The advantage of the `f.(A)` syntax is that which functions are vectorizable need not be decided upon in advance by the library writer.
[src:julia/manual-functions] More generally, `f.(args...)` is actually equivalent to `broadcast(f, args...)`, which allows you to operate on multiple arrays (even of different shapes), or a mix of arrays and scalars (see Broadcasting).
[src:julia/manual-functions] Keyword arguments are not broadcasted over, but are simply passed through to each call of the function.
[src:julia/manual-functions] For example, `round.(x, digits=3)` is equivalent to `broadcast(x -> round(x, digits=3), x)`.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Moreover, *nested* `f.(args...)` calls are *fused* into a single `broadcast` loop.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Technically, the fusion stops as soon as a "non-dot" function call is encountered; for example, in `sin.(sort(cos.(X)))` the `sin` and `cos` loops cannot be merged because of the intervening `sort` function.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Finally, the maximum efficiency is typically achieved when the output array of a vectorized operation is *pre-allocated*, so that repeated calls do not allocate new arrays over and over again for the results (see Pre-allocating outputs).
[src:julia/manual-functions] A convenient syntax for this is `X .= ...`, which is equivalent to `broadcast!(identity, X, ...)` except that, as above, the `broadcast!` loop is fused with any nested "dot" calls.
[src:julia/manual-functions] For example, `X .= sin.(Y)` is equivalent to `broadcast!(sin, X, Y)`, overwriting `X` with `sin.(Y)` in-place.
[src:julia/manual-functions] If the left-hand side is an array-indexing expression, e.g.
[src:julia/manual-functions] `X[begin+1:end] .= sin.(Y)`, then it translates to `broadcast!` on a `view`, e.g.
[src:julia/manual-functions] `broadcast!(sin, view(X, firstindex(X)+1:lastindex(X)), Y)`, so that the left-hand side is updated in-place.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Since adding dots to many operations and function calls in an expression can be tedious and lead to code that is difficult to read, the macro `@.` is provided to convert *every* function call, operation, and assignment in an expression into the "dotted" version.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Binary (or unary) operators like `.+` are handled with the same mechanism: they are equivalent to `broadcast` calls and are fused with other nested "dot" calls.
[src:julia/manual-functions] `X .+= Y` etcetera is equivalent to `X .= X .+ Y` and results in a fused in-place assignment; see also dot operators.
[src:julia/manual-functions] All functions in the fused broadcast are always called for every element of the result.
[src:julia/manual-functions] Thus `X .+ σ .* randn.()` will add a mask of independent and identically sampled random values to each element of the array `X`, but `X .+ σ .* randn()` will add the *same* random sample to each element.
[src:julia/manual-functions] In cases where the fused computation is constant along one or more axes of the broadcast iteration, it may be possible to leverage a space-time tradeoff and allocate intermediate values to reduce the number of computations.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Object orientation allows some flexibility in statically typed languages by letting code be written without the precise types of values being known at compile time.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The ability to write code that can operate on different types is called polymorphism.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] All code in classic dynamically typed languages is polymorphic: only by explicitly checking types, or when objects fail to support operations at run-time, are the types of any values ever restricted.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Julia's type system is dynamic, but gains some of the advantages of static type systems by making it possible to indicate that certain values are of specific types.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] This can be of great assistance in generating efficient code, but even more significantly, it allows method dispatch on the types of function arguments to be deeply integrated with the language.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Method dispatch is explored in detail in Methods, but is rooted in the type system presented here.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The default behavior in Julia when types are omitted is to allow values to be of any type.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Thus, one can write many useful Julia functions without ever explicitly using types.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] When additional expressiveness is needed, however, it is easy to gradually introduce explicit type annotations into previously "untyped" code.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Adding annotations serves three primary purposes: to take advantage of Julia's powerful multiple-dispatch mechanism, to improve human readability, and to catch programmer errors.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Describing Julia in the lingo of type systems, it is: dynamic, nominative and parametric.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Generic types can be parameterized, and the hierarchical relationships between types are explicitly declared, rather than implied by compatible structure.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] One particularly distinctive feature of Julia's type system is that concrete types may not subtype each other: all concrete types are final and may only have abstract types as their supertypes.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] While this might at first seem unduly restrictive, it has many beneficial consequences with surprisingly few drawbacks.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] It turns out that being able to inherit behavior is much more important than being able to inherit structure, and inheriting both causes significant difficulties in traditional object-oriented languages.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Julia's type system is designed to be powerful and expressive, yet clear, intuitive and unobtrusive.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Many Julia programmers may never feel the need to write code that explicitly uses types.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Some kinds of programming, however, become clearer, simpler, faster and more robust with declared types.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The `::` operator can be used to attach type annotations to expressions and variables in programs.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] To provide extra type information to the compiler, which can then improve performance in some cases.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] When appended to an expression computing a value, the `::` operator is read as "is an instance of".
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] It can be used anywhere to assert that the value of the expression on the left is an instance of the type on the right.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] When the type on the right is concrete, the value on the left must have that type as its implementation – recall that all concrete types are final, so no implementation is a subtype of any other.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] When the type is abstract, it suffices for the value to be implemented by a concrete type that is a subtype of the abstract type.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] This allows a type assertion to be attached to any expression in-place.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] When appended to a variable on the left-hand side of an assignment, or as part of a `local` declaration, the `::` operator means something a bit different: it declares the variable to always have the specified type, like a type declaration in a statically-typed language such as C.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] This feature is useful for avoiding performance "gotchas" that could occur if one of the assignments to a variable changed its type unexpectedly.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] and applies to the whole current scope, even before the declaration.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] As of Julia 1.8, type declarations can now be used in global scope i.e. type annotations can be added to global variables to make accessing them type stable.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Returning from this function behaves just like an assignment to a variable with a declared type: the value is always converted to `Float64`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Abstract types cannot be instantiated, and serve only as nodes in the type graph, thereby describing sets of related concrete types: those concrete types which are their descendants.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] We begin with abstract types even though they have no instantiation because they are the backbone of the type system: they form the conceptual hierarchy which makes Julia's type system more than just a collection of object implementations.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Recall that in Integers and Floating-Point Numbers, we introduced a variety of concrete types of numeric values: `Int8`, `UInt8`, `Int16`, `UInt16`, `Int32`, `UInt32`, `Int64`, `UInt64`, `Int128`, `UInt128`, `Float16`, `Float32`, and `Float64`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Although they have different representation sizes, `Int8`, `Int16`, `Int32`, `Int64` and `Int128` all have in common that they are signed integer types.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Likewise `UInt8`, `UInt16`, `UInt32`, `UInt64` and `UInt128` are all unsigned integer types, while `Float16`, `Float32` and `Float64` are distinct in being floating-point types rather than integers.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] It is common for a piece of code to make sense, for example, only if its arguments are some kind of integer, but not really depend on what particular *kind* of integer.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] For example, the greatest common denominator algorithm works for all kinds of integers, but will not work for floating-point numbers.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Abstract types allow the construction of a hierarchy of types, providing a context into which concrete types can fit.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] This allows you, for example, to easily program to any type that is an integer, without restricting an algorithm to a specific type of integer.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Abstract types are declared using the `abstract type` keyword.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The `abstract type` keyword introduces a new abstract type, whose name is given by `«name»`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] This name can be optionally followed by `<:` and an already-existing type, indicating that the newly declared abstract type is a subtype of this "parent" type.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] When no supertype is given, the default supertype is `Any` – a predefined abstract type that all objects are instances of and all types are subtypes of.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] In type theory, `Any` is commonly called "top" because it is at the apex of the type graph.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Julia also has a predefined abstract "bottom" type, at the nadir of the type graph, which is written as `Union{}`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] It is the exact opposite of `Any`: no object is an instance of `Union{}` and all types are supertypes of `Union{}`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The `Number` type is a direct child type of `Any`, and `Real` is its child.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] In turn, `Real` has two children (it has more, but only two are shown here; we'll get to the others later): `Integer` and `AbstractFloat`, separating the world into representations of integers and representations of real numbers.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Representations of real numbers include floating-point types, but also include other types, such as rationals.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] `AbstractFloat` includes only floating-point representations of real numbers.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Integers are further subdivided into `Signed` and `Unsigned` varieties.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The `<:` operator in general means "is a subtype of", and, used in declarations like those above, declares the right-hand type to be an immediate supertype of the newly declared type.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] An important use of abstract types is to provide default implementations for concrete types.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The first thing to note is that the above argument declarations are equivalent to `x::Any` and `y::Any`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] When this function is invoked, say as `myplus(2,5)`, the dispatcher chooses the most specific method named `myplus` that matches the given arguments.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] and finally, it invokes this specific method.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Thus, abstract types allow programmers to write generic functions that can later be used as the default method by many combinations of concrete types.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Thanks to multiple dispatch, the programmer has full control over whether the default or more specific method is used.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] An important point to note is that there is no loss in performance if the programmer relies on a function whose arguments are abstract types, because it is recompiled for each tuple of concrete argument types with which it is invoked.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] It is almost always preferable to wrap an existing primitive type in a new composite type than to define your own primitive type.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] This functionality exists to allow Julia to bootstrap the standard primitive types that LLVM supports.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Once they are defined, there is very little reason to define more.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] A primitive type is a concrete type whose data consists of plain old bits.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Classic examples of primitive types are integers and floating-point values.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Unlike most languages, Julia lets you declare your own primitive types, rather than providing only a fixed set of built-in ones.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The number of bits indicates how much storage the type requires and the name gives the new type a name.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] A primitive type can optionally be declared to be a subtype of some supertype.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] If a supertype is omitted, then the type defaults to having `Any` as its immediate supertype.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The declaration of `Bool` above therefore means that a boolean value takes eight bits to store, and has `Integer` as its immediate supertype.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Currently, only sizes that are multiples of 8 bits are supported and you are likely to experience LLVM bugs with sizes other than those used above.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Therefore, boolean values, although they really need just a single bit, cannot be declared to be any smaller than eight bits.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The types `Bool`, `Int8` and `UInt8` all have identical representations: they are eight-bit chunks of memory.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Since Julia's type system is nominative, however, they are not interchangeable despite having identical structure.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] A fundamental difference between them is that they have different supertypes: `Bool`'s direct supertype is `Integer`, `Int8`'s is `Signed`, and `UInt8`'s is `Unsigned`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] All other differences between `Bool`, `Int8`, and `UInt8` are matters of behavior – the way functions are defined to act when given objects of these types as arguments.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] This is why a nominative type system is necessary: if structure determined type, which in turn dictates behavior, then it would be impossible to make `Bool` behave any differently than `Int8` or `UInt8`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Composite types are called records, structs, or objects in various languages.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] A composite type is a collection of named fields, an instance of which can be treated as a single value.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] In many languages, composite types are the only kind of user-definable type, and they are by far the most commonly used user-defined type in Julia as well.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] In mainstream object oriented languages, such as C++, Java, Python and Ruby, composite types also have named functions associated with them, and the combination is called an "object".
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] In purer object-oriented languages, such as Ruby or Smalltalk, all values are objects whether they are composites or not.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] In less pure object oriented languages, including C++ and Java, some values, such as integers and floating-point values, are not objects, while instances of user-defined composite types are true objects with associated methods.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] In Julia, all values are objects, but functions are not bundled with the objects they operate on.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] This is necessary since Julia chooses which method of a function to use by multiple dispatch, meaning that the types of *all* of a function's arguments are considered when selecting a method, rather than just the first one (see Methods for more information on methods and dispatch).
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Thus, it would be inappropriate for functions to "belong" to only their first argument.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Organizing methods into function objects rather than having named bags of methods "inside" each object ends up being a highly beneficial aspect of the language design.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Fields with no type annotation default to `Any`, and can accordingly hold any type of value.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] When a type is applied like a function it is called a *constructor*.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Two constructors are generated automatically (these are called *default constructors*).
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] One accepts any arguments and calls `convert` to convert them to the types of the fields, and the other accepts arguments that match the field types exactly.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The reason both of these are generated is that this makes it easier to add new definitions without inadvertently replacing a default constructor.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Since the `bar` field is unconstrained in type, any value will do.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] You may find a list of field names using the `fieldnames` function.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Composite objects declared with `struct` are *immutable*; they cannot be modified after construction.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] An immutable object might contain mutable objects, such as arrays, as fields.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Those contained objects will remain mutable; only the fields of the immutable object itself cannot be changed to point to different objects.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Where required, mutable composite objects can be declared with the keyword `mutable struct`, to be discussed in the next section.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] There is much more to say about how instances of composite types are created, but that discussion depends on both Parametric Types and on Methods, and is sufficiently important to be addressed in its own section: Constructors.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] For many user-defined types `X`, you may want to define a method `Base.broadcastable(x::X) = Ref(x)` so that instances of that type act as 0-dimensional "scalars" for broadcasting.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] An extra interface between the fields and the user can be provided through Instance Properties.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] This grants more control on what can be accessed and modified using the `bar.baz` notation.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] In order to support mutation, such objects are generally allocated on the heap, and have stable memory addresses.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] A mutable object is like a little container that might hold different values over time, and so can only be reliably identified with its address.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] In contrast, an instance of an immutable type is associated with specific field values –- the field values alone tell you everything about the object.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] In deciding whether to make a type mutable, ask whether two instances with the same field values would be considered identical, or if they might need to change independently over time.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] If they would be considered identical, the type should probably be immutable.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] In cases where one or more fields of an otherwise mutable struct is known to be immutable, one can declare these fields as such using `const` as shown below.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] This enables some, but not all of the optimizations of immutable structs, and can be used to enforce invariants on the particular fields marked as `const`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] `const` annotating fields of mutable structs requires at least Julia 1.8.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The three kinds of types (abstract, primitive, composite) discussed in the previous sections are actually all closely related.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] A `DataType` may be abstract or concrete.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] If it is concrete, it has a specified size, storage layout, and (optionally) field names.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Thus a primitive type is a `DataType` with nonzero size, but no field names.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] A composite type is a `DataType` that has field names or is empty (zero size).
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Every concrete value in the system is an instance of some `DataType`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The compilers for many languages have an internal union construct for reasoning about types; Julia simply exposes it to the programmer.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The Julia compiler is able to generate efficient code in the presence of `Union` types with a small number of types , by generating specialized code in separate branches for each possible type.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] A particularly useful case of a `Union` type is `Union{T, Nothing}`, where `T` can be any type and `Nothing` is the singleton type whose only instance is the object `nothing`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] This pattern is the Julia equivalent of `Nullable`, `Option` or `Maybe` types in other languages.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Declaring a function argument or a field as `Union{T, Nothing}` allows setting it either to a value of type `T`, or to `nothing` to indicate that there is no value.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] See this FAQ entry for more information.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] An important and powerful feature of Julia's type system is that it is parametric: types can take parameters, so that type declarations actually introduce a whole family of new types – one for each possible combination of parameter values.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] There are many languages that support some version of generic programming, wherein data structures and algorithms to manipulate them may be specified without specifying the exact types involved.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] For example, some form of generic programming exists in ML, Haskell, Ada, Eiffel, C++, Java, C#, F#, and Scala, just to name a few.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Some of these languages support true parametric polymorphism (e.g.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] ML, Haskell, Scala), while others support ad-hoc, template-based styles of generic programming (e.g.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] With so many different varieties of generic programming and parametric types in various languages, we won't even attempt to compare Julia's parametric types to other languages, but will instead focus on explaining Julia's system in its own right.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] We will note, however, that because Julia is a dynamically typed language and doesn't need to make all type decisions at compile time, many traditional difficulties encountered in static parametric type systems can be relatively easily handled.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] All declared types (the `DataType` variety) can be parameterized, with the same syntax in each case.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] We will discuss them in the following order: first, parametric composite types, then parametric abstract types, and finally parametric primitive types.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] This declaration defines a new parametric type, `Point{T}`, holding two "coordinates" of type `T`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Well, that's precisely the point of parametric types: it can be any type at all (or a value of any bits type, actually, although here it's clearly used as a type).
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] `Point{Float64}` is a concrete type equivalent to the type defined by replacing `T` in the definition of `Point` with `Float64`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Thus, this single declaration actually declares an unlimited number of types: `Point{Float64}`, `Point{AbstractString}`, `Point{Int64}`, etc.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The type `Point{Float64}` is a point whose coordinates are 64-bit floating-point values, while the type `Point{AbstractString}` is a "point" whose "coordinates" are string objects (see Strings).
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] This last point is *very* important: even though `Float64 <: Real` we **DO NOT** have `Point{Float64} <: Point{Real}`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] In other words, in the parlance of type theory, Julia's type parameters are *invariant*, rather than being covariant (or even contravariant).
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] More examples will be discussed later in Methods.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] How does one construct a `Point` object?
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Only one default constructor is generated for parametric types, since overriding it is not possible.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] This constructor accepts any arguments and converts them to the field types.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] In many cases, it is redundant to provide the type of `Point` object one wants to construct, since the types of arguments to the constructor call already implicitly provide type information.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] In the case of `Point`, the type of `T` is unambiguously implied if and only if the two arguments to `Point` have the same type.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Constructor methods to appropriately handle such mixed cases can be defined, but that will not be discussed until later on in Constructors.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] With this declaration, `Pointy{T}` is a distinct abstract type for each type or integer value of `T`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The notation `Pointy{<:Real}` can be used to express the Julia analogue of a *covariant* type, while `Pointy{>:Int}` the analogue of a *contravariant* type, but technically these represent *sets* of types (see UnionAll Types).
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Much as plain old abstract types serve to create a useful hierarchy of types over concrete types, parametric abstract types serve the same purpose with respect to parametric composite types.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] What purpose do parametric abstract types like `Pointy` serve?
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Now both `Point{Float64}` and `DiagPoint{Float64}` are implementations of the `Pointy{Float64}` abstraction, and similarly for every other possible choice of type `T`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] This allows programming to a common interface shared by all `Pointy` objects, implemented for both `Point` and `DiagPoint`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] This cannot be fully demonstrated, however, until we have introduced methods and dispatch in the next section, Methods.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] There are situations where it may not make sense for type parameters to range freely over all possible types.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] It only makes sense to take ratios of integer values, so the parameter type `T` is restricted to being a subtype of `Integer`, and a ratio of integers represents a value on the real number line, so any `Rational` is an instance of the `Real` abstraction.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Tuples are an abstraction of the arguments of a function – without the function itself.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The salient aspects of a function's arguments are their order and their types.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Therefore a tuple type is similar to a parameterized immutable type where each parameter is the type of one field.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Tuple values are written with parentheses and commas.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Intuitively, this corresponds to the type of a function's arguments being a subtype of the function's signature (when the signature matches).
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Moreover `Vararg{T}` corresponds to zero or more elements of type `T`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Vararg tuple types are used to represent the arguments accepted by varargs methods (see Varargs Functions).
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The special value `Vararg{T,N}` (when used as the last parameter of a tuple type) corresponds to exactly `N` elements of type `T`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] `NTuple{N,T}` is a convenient alias for `Tuple{Vararg{T,N}}`, i.e. a tuple type containing exactly `N` elements of type `T`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Named tuples are instances of the `NamedTuple` type, which has two parameters: a tuple of symbols giving the field names, and a tuple type giving the field types.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] For convenience, `NamedTuple` types are printed using the `@NamedTuple` macro which provides a convenient `struct`-like syntax for declaring these types via `key::Type` declarations, where an omitted `::Type` corresponds to `::Any`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] A `NamedTuple` type can be used as a constructor, accepting a single tuple argument.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] If field types are specified, the arguments are converted.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Otherwise the types of the arguments are used directly.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Primitive types can also be declared parametrically.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Thus, `Ptr{Float64}` and `Ptr{Int64}` are distinct types, even though they have identical representations.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] We have said that a parametric type like `Ptr` acts as a supertype of all its instances (`Ptr{Int64}` etc.).
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] `Ptr` itself cannot be a normal data type, since without knowing the type of the referenced data the type clearly cannot be used for memory operations.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The answer is that `Ptr` (or other parametric types like `Array`) is a different kind of type called a `UnionAll` type.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Such a type expresses the *iterated union* of types for all values of some parameter.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] `UnionAll` types are usually written using the keyword `where`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] For example `Ptr` could be more accurately written as `Ptr{T} where T`, meaning all values whose type is `Ptr{T}` for some value of `T`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] In this context, the parameter `T` is also often called a "type variable" since it is like a variable that ranges over types.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Each `where` introduces a single type variable, so these expressions are nested for types with multiple parameters, for example `Array{T,N} where N where T`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The type application syntax `A{B,C}` requires `A` to be a `UnionAll` type, and first substitutes `B` for the outermost type variable in `A`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The result is expected to be another `UnionAll` type, into which `C` is then substituted.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] This explains why it is possible to partially instantiate a type, as in `Array{Float64}`: the first parameter value has been fixed, but the second still ranges over all possible values.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Using explicit `where` syntax, any subset of parameters can be fixed.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] For example, the type of all 1-dimensional arrays can be written as `Array{T,1} where T`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Type variables can be restricted with subtype relations.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] `Array{T} where T<:Integer` refers to all arrays whose element type is some kind of `Integer`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The syntax `Array{<:Integer}` is a convenient shorthand for `Array{T} where T<:Integer`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Type variables can have both lower and upper bounds.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] `Array{T} where Int<:T<:Number` refers to all arrays of `Number`s that are able to contain `Int`s (since `T` must be at least as big as `Int`).
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The syntax `where T>:Int` also works to specify only the lower bound of a type variable, and `Array{>:Int}` is equivalent to `Array{T} where T>:Int`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Since `where` expressions nest, type variable bounds can refer to outer type variables.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] For example `Tuple{T,Array{S}} where S<:AbstractArray{T} where T<:Real` refers to 2-tuples whose first element is some `Real`, and whose second element is an `Array` of any kind of array whose element type contains the type of the first tuple element.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The `where` keyword itself can be nested inside a more complex declaration.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Type `T1` defines a 1-dimensional array of 1-dimensional arrays; each of the inner arrays consists of objects of the same type, but this type may vary from one inner array to the next.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] On the other hand, type `T2` defines a 1-dimensional array of 1-dimensional arrays all of whose inner arrays must have the same type.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Note that `T2` is an abstract type, e.g., `Array{Array{Int,1},1} <: T2`, whereas `T1` is a concrete type.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] As a consequence, `T1` can be constructed with a zero-argument constructor `a=T1()` but `T2` cannot.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] This is equivalent to `const Vector = Array{T,1} where T`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Writing `Vector{Float64}` is equivalent to writing `Array{Float64,1}`, and the umbrella type `Vector` has as instances all `Array` objects where the second parameter – the number of array dimensions – is 1, regardless of what the element type is.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] In languages where parametric types must always be specified in full, this is not especially helpful, but in Julia, this allows one to write just `Vector` for the abstract type including all one-dimensional dense arrays of any element type.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Immutable composite types with no fields are called *singletons*.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] `Base.issingletontype` can be used to check if a type is a singleton type.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Abstract types cannot be singleton types by construction.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] The `===` function confirms that the constructed instances of `NoFields` are actually one and the same.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Parametric types can be singleton types when the above condition holds.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Each function has its own type, which is a subtype of `Function`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Note how `typeof(foo41)` prints as itself.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Types of functions defined at top-level are singletons.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] When necessary, you can compare them with `===`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Closures also have their own type, which is usually printed with names that end in `#<number>`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Names and types for functions defined at different locations are distinct, but not guaranteed to be printed the same way across sessions.
[src:julia/manual-types-p01] Types of closures are not necessarily singletons.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] For each type `T`, `Type{T}` is an abstract parametric type whose only instance is the object `T`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] Until we discuss Parametric Methods and conversions, it is difficult to explain the utility of this construct, but in short, it allows one to specialize function behavior on specific types as *values*.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] This is useful for writing methods (especially parametric ones) whose behavior depends on a type that is given as an explicit argument rather than implied by the type of one of its arguments.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] In other words, `isa(A, Type{B})` is true if and only if `A` and `B` are the same object and that object is a type.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] While `Type` is part of Julia's type hierarchy like any other abstract parametric type, it is not commonly used outside method signatures except in some special cases.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] Sometimes it is convenient to introduce a new name for an already expressible type.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] This can be done with a simple assignment statement.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] Of course, this depends on what `Int` is aliased to – but that is predefined to be the correct type – either `Int32` or `Int64`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] (Note that unlike `Int`, `Float` does not exist as a type alias for a specific sized `AbstractFloat`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] Since types in Julia are themselves objects, ordinary functions can operate on them.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] Some functions that are particularly useful for working with or exploring types have already been introduced, such as the `<:` operator, which indicates whether its left hand operand is a subtype of its right hand operand.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] The `typeof` function, already used throughout the manual in examples, returns the type of its argument.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] Another operation that applies to some types is `supertype`, which reveals a type's supertype.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] Often, one wants to customize how instances of a type are displayed.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] This is accomplished by overloading the `show` function.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] Here, we've added a custom constructor function so that it can take arguments of different `Real` types and promote them to a common type (see Constructors and Conversion and Promotion).
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] (Of course, we would have to define lots of other methods, too, to make it act like a `Number`, e.g.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] `+`, `*`, `one`, `zero`, promotion rules and so on.) By default, instances of this type display rather simply, with information about the type name and the field values, as e.g.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] More fine-grained control over display of `Polar` objects is possible.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] In particular, sometimes one wants both a verbose multi-line printing format, used for displaying a single object in the REPL and other interactive environments, and also a more compact single-line format used for `print` or for displaying the object as part of another object (e.g. in an array).
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] where the single-line `show(io, z)` form is still used for an array of `Polar` values.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] Moreover, you can also define `show` methods for other MIME types in order to enable richer display (HTML, images, etcetera) of objects in environments that support this (e.g.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] As a rule of thumb, the single-line `show` method should print a valid Julia expression for creating the shown object.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] When this `show` method contains infix operators, such as the multiplication operator (`*`) in our single-line `show` method for `Polar` above, it may not parse correctly when printed as part of another object.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] Because the operator `^` has higher precedence than `*` (see Operator Precedence and Associativity), this output does not faithfully represent the expression `a ^ 2` which should be equal to `(3.0 * exp(4.0im)) ^ 2`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] The method defined above adds parentheses around the call to `show` when the precedence of the calling operator is higher than or equal to the precedence of multiplication.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] In some cases, it is useful to adjust the behavior of `show` methods depending on the context.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] This can be achieved via the `IOContext` type, which allows passing contextual properties together with a wrapped IO stream.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] This new compact representation will be used when the passed IO stream is an `IOContext` object with the `:compact` property set.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] See the `IOContext` documentation for a list of common properties which can be used to adjust printing.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] Here is a brief summary of the different output functions in Julia and how they are related.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] Most new types should only need to define `show` methods, if anything.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] It is also helpful to be familiar with the metadata that can be attached to an `io` stream by an `IOContext` wrapper.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] For example, the REPL sets the `:limit => true` flag from `display` for an evaluated expression, in order to limit the output to fit in the terminal; you can query this flag with `get(io, :limit, false)`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] And when displaying an object contained within, for example, a multi-column matrix, the `:compact => true` flag could be set, which you can query with `get(io, :compact, false)`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] In Julia, you can't dispatch on a *value* such as `true` or `false`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] However, you can dispatch on parametric types, and Julia allows you to include "plain bits" values (Types, Symbols, Integers, floating-point numbers, tuples, etc.) as type parameters.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] A common example is the dimensionality parameter in `Array{T,N}`, where `T` is a type (e.g., `Float64`) but `N` is just an `Int`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] You can create your own custom types that take values as parameters, and use them to control dispatch of custom types.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] By way of illustration of this idea, let's introduce the parametric type `Val{x}`, and its constructor `Val(x) = Val{x}()`, which serves as a customary way to exploit this technique for cases where you don't need a more elaborate hierarchy.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] There is no more to the implementation of `Val` than this.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] Some functions in Julia's standard library accept `Val` instances as arguments, and you can also use it to write your own functions.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] For consistency across Julia, the call site should always pass a `Val` *instance* rather than using a *type*, i.e., use `foo(Val(:bar))` rather than `foo(Val{:bar})`.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] It's worth noting that it's extremely easy to mis-use parametric "value" types, including `Val`; in unfavorable cases, you can easily end up making the performance of your code much *worse*.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] In particular, you would never want to write actual code as illustrated above.
[src:julia/manual-types-p02] For more information about the proper (and improper) uses of `Val`, please read the more extensive discussion in the performance tips.
[src:julia/manual-variables] A variable, in Julia, is a name associated (or bound) to a value.
[src:julia/manual-variables] It's useful when you want to store a value (that you obtained after some math, for example) for later use.
[src:julia/manual-variables] Julia provides an extremely flexible system for naming variables.
[src:julia/manual-variables] Variable names are case-sensitive, and have no semantic meaning (that is, the language will not treat variables differently based on their names).
[src:julia/manual-variables] In the Julia REPL and several other Julia editing environments, you can type many Unicode math symbols by typing the backslashed LaTeX symbol name followed by tab.
[src:julia/manual-variables] Note that in versions prior to Julia 1.12, these errors depended on *use* rather than definition of the conflicting binding.
[src:julia/manual-variables] Subsequent characters may also include ! and digits (0-9 and other characters in categories Nd/No), as well as other Unicode code points: diacritics and other modifying marks (categories Mn/Mc/Me/Sk), some punctuation connectors (category Pc), primes, and a few other characters.
[src:julia/manual-variables] Operators like `+` are also valid identifiers, but are parsed specially.
[src:julia/manual-variables] In some contexts, operators can be used just like variables; for example `(+)` refers to the addition function, and `(+) = f` will reassign it.
[src:julia/manual-variables] Most of the Unicode infix operators (in category Sm), such as `⊕`, are parsed as infix operators and are available for user-defined methods (e.g. you can use `const ⊗ = kron` to define `⊗` as an infix Kronecker product).
[src:julia/manual-variables] Operators can also be suffixed with modifying marks, primes, and sub/superscripts, e.g.
[src:julia/manual-variables] `+̂ₐ″` is parsed as an infix operator with the same precedence as `+`.
[src:julia/manual-variables] A space is required between an operator that ends with a subscript/superscript letter and a subsequent variable name.
[src:julia/manual-variables] For example, if `+ᵃ` is an operator, then `+ᵃx` must be written as `+ᵃ x` to distinguish it from `+ ᵃx` where `ᵃx` is the variable name.
[src:julia/manual-variables] A particular class of variable names is one that contains only underscores.
[src:julia/manual-variables] I.e. they can only be assigned values, which are immediately discarded, and their values cannot be used in any way.
[src:julia/manual-variables] Some Unicode characters are considered to be equivalent in identifiers.
[src:julia/manual-variables] Different ways of entering Unicode combining characters (e.g., accents) are treated as equivalent (specifically, Julia identifiers are NFC.
[src:julia/manual-variables] Julia also includes a few non-standard equivalences for characters that are visually similar and are easily entered by some input methods.
[src:julia/manual-variables] The Unicode characters `ɛ` (U+025B: Latin small letter open e) and `µ` (U+00B5: micro sign) are treated as equivalent to the corresponding Greek letters.
[src:julia/manual-variables] The middle dot `·` (U+00B7) and the Greek interpunct `·` (U+0387) are both treated as the mathematical dot operator `⋅` (U+22C5).
[src:julia/manual-variables] The minus sign `−` (U+2212) is treated as equivalent to the hyphen-minus sign `-` (U+002D).
[src:julia/manual-variables] An assignment `variable = value` "binds" the name `variable` to the `value` computed on the right-hand side, and the whole assignment is treated by Julia as an expression equal to the right-hand-side `value`.
[src:julia/manual-variables] This means that assignments can be *chained* (the same `value` assigned to multiple variables with `variable1 = variable2 = value`) or used in other expressions, and is also why their result is shown in the REPL as the value of the right-hand side.
[src:julia/manual-variables] A common confusion is the distinction between *assignment* (giving a new "name" to a value) and *mutation* (changing a value).
[src:julia/manual-variables] If you run `a = 2` followed by `a = 3`, you have changed the "name" `a` to refer to a new value `3` … you haven't changed the number `2`, so `2+2` will still give `4` and not `6`!
[src:julia/manual-variables] Here, the line `b = a` does *not* make a copy of the array `a`, it simply binds the name `b` to the *same* array `a`: both `b` and `a` "point" to one array `[1,2,3]` in memory.
[src:julia/manual-variables] That is, `a[i] = value` (an alias for `setindex!`) *mutates* an existing array object in memory, accessible via either `a` or `b`.
[src:julia/manual-variables] Subsequently setting `a = 3.14159` does not change this array, it simply binds `a` to a different object; the array is still accessible via `b`.
[src:julia/manual-variables] Another common syntax to mutate an existing object is `a.field = value` (an alias for `setproperty!`), which can be used to change a `mutable struct`.
[src:julia/manual-variables] There is also mutation via dot assignment, for example `b .= 5:7` (which mutates our array `b` in-place to contain `[5,6,7]`), as part of Julia's vectorized "dot" syntax.
[src:julia/manual-variables] When you call a function in Julia, it behaves as if you *assigned* the argument values to new variable names corresponding to the function arguments, as discussed in Argument-Passing Behavior.
[src:julia/manual-variables] For more information about stylistic conventions, see the Style Guide.
